<subSubSection id="C9C6F1F7FF5ACE85FCD5F886D9603B4E" lastPageId="216" lastPageNumber="217" pageId="215" pageNumber="216" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8163A27CFF5ACE85FCD5F886D9603B4E" blockId="215.[810,1451,1879,2093]" lastBlockId="216.[136,778,1821,2011]" lastPageId="216" lastPageNumber="217" pageId="215" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5ACE8AFCD5F886D8F73B5F" bold="true" box="[810,932,1879,1905]" pageId="215" pageNumber="216">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF5ACE8AFB90F886D8243BB9" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="215" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, males of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5ACE8AFBF7F8ACDFF33BB8" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1032,1184,1917,1943]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="215" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatus">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5ACE8AFBF7F8ACDFF33BB8" box="[1032,1184,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="215" pageNumber="216">A. excavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5ACE8AFC26F873DF373B92" authorityName="Rios" authorityYear="2014" box="[985,1124,1954,1980]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="215" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goloboffi">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5ACE8AFC26F873DF373B92" box="[985,1124,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="215" pageNumber="216">A. goloboffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the thinner and slender bulb (
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF5ACE8AFC93F819DF8E3BCC" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[876,1245,1991,2018]" pageId="215" pageNumber="216" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 39 E–G) and from those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5ACE8AFC34F83CDF1F3429" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[971,1100,2029,2055]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="215" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balcarce">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5ACE8AFC34F83CDF1F3429" box="[971,1100,2029,2055]" italics="true" pageId="215" pageNumber="216">A. balcarce</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the poorly developed BTA, well-developed PA. Females present small subquadrate spermathecae with a small external apical lobe (Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff, 2018, fig. 40 C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
